Random Number Generation

Monte Carlo methods rely mostly on being able to generate random numbers (often with a given Probability Density function), thus a good random number generator is important to guarantee the quality of the output of Monte Carlo method.However, what we can do on a computer, is develop some sort of algorithm for generating a sequence of numbers that approximates the properties of random numbers. When numbers are produced by some sort of algorithm or formula that simulates the values of a random variable X, they are called pseudorandom numbers. And the algorithm is called a pseudorandom number generator (or PRNG). I have explored the field of random number generation in detail in my course on Fundamentals of Cryptography. Lets explore a simple Random Unior

PRNGs can also be used in data partitioning and sampling methods. Here we are exploring a simple random number generator in 3 dimension and finding its flaws.

randu <- local({
  seed <- 1
  a <- 2 ^ 16 + 3 # multiplier
  m <- 2 ^ 31 # modulus
  function (unif = TRUE) {
    seed <<- (a * seed) %% m
    if (unif) seed / m else seed
  }
})

randu.setseed <- function (seed)
  environment(randu)$seed <- seed

# more general, using higher-order function:
lehmer.prng <- function (a, m, r0 = 1) {
  local({
    seed <- r0
    function (unif = TRUE) {
      seed <<- (a * seed) %% m
      if (unif) seed / m else seed
    }
  })
}
lehmer.setseed <- function (l, seed)
  environment(l)$seed <- seed

randu <- lehmer.prng(2 ^ 16 + 3, 2 ^ 31)

# demo
n <- 10000 # #samples
x <- y <- z <-  numeric(n)
x[1] <- randu(); y[1] <- randu(); z[1] <- randu()
for (i in 2:n) {
  x[i] <- y[i - 1]; y[i] <- z[i - 1]; z[i] <- randu()
}
